Forties Falls on Trafigura Sale; Urals in Northwest Europe Drops

-- B y   S h e r r y   S u
-- 
2011-03-25T17:45:41Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-25/forties-falls-on-trafigura-sale-urals-in-northwest-europe-drops.html
North Sea Forties crude fell as
Trafigura Beheer BV sold a cargo. Russian Urals reached a new
32-month low in northwest  Europe  even after Glencore
International AG bid at a narrower discount.  North Sea  Trafigura sold one cargo for loading April 4 to April 6 to
Royal Dutch Shell Plc at 25 cents a barrel below benchmark Dated
Brent, the biggest discount traded in more than two weeks,
according to a survey of traders and brokers monitoring the
daily Platts trading window. The company yesterday offered the
cargo at 20 cents less than Dated Brent.  Total SA sold a shipment for April 8 to April 10 to
ConocoPhillips at 10 cents above Dated Brent, the survey showed.
Statoil ASA failed to buy a consignment for April 8 to April 12
at 10 cents less than Dated Brent.  Reported  North Sea  market activity typically occurs during
the Platts window that ends at 4:30 p.m. in London. Prior to the
window, Forties loading 10 to 21 days in the future cost 20
cents less than Dated Brent, compared with a discount of 14
cents yesterday, according to data compiled by Bloomberg.  Brent for May settlement traded at $115.70 a barrel on the
London-based ICE Futures Europe exchange at the close of the
window, down from $115.77 yesterday. The June contract was at
$115.56, 14 cents below May.  Glencore sought to buy 100,000 metric tons of Urals for
April 4 to April 8 delivery to Rotterdam at $3.95 a barrel below
Dated Brent without success, according to the survey. This
compared with a discount of $4.30 for a trade yesterday.  Petroplus Holdings AG withdrew its earlier bid for April 7
to April 11 at $4.35 less than Dated Brent, the survey showed.  Urals was assessed at $4.22 below Dated Brent today, the
lowest since July 23, 2008, the Bloomberg data show. The
discount has widened 88% so far this month.  Statoil said production at its Brage oil field in the North
Sea resumed yesterday, according to a company spokesman. The
company halted production from the platform on March 21 because
of a rust hole in the flaring pipe, Dagens Naeringsliv reported
today.  Rosneft Oil Co. awarded its Urals crude tender for 400,000
metric tons loading in April from the Baltic Sea Primorsk port
to Vitol Group, according to three traders who participate in
the market.  Mediterranean  No bids or offers of Urals were made in the Mediterranean.
Eni SpA yesterday failed to buy 80,000 tons for loading April 3
to April 7 at $3.75 below Dated Brent.  Urals was valued at $3.60 less than Dated Brent today, up
from yesterdayâ€™s 32-month low of a discount of $3.80, Bloomberg
data showed.  West Africa  CPC Corp. bought via a tender 4 million barrels, or four
cargoes, of Angolan Cabinda and Nemba crude for loading in May,
according to three traders who participate in the market.  Chevron Corp., Vitol Group, ConocoPhillips and Sonangol EP
were awarded the tender, the people said.  To contact the reporter on this story:
